comment.body:
Minor: doc clarification
The word "data" and "message" seem to be used interchangeable throughout the document, which may cause confusion.

According to the RFC 3261, "SIP messages are either requests or responses", while data may not always refer to an entire message. So better clarify and be precise here.

I would also suggest to use word processor or AI to catch grammatical or spelling errors.

pull_request.title: Add TLS initial receive timeout for server connection
pull_request.body:
For TCP there is a setting to close the incoming connection if there's no data received after a successful accept (`PJSIP_TCP_INITIAL_TIMEOUT`).

There is `PJSIP_TRANSPORT_SERVER_IDLE_TIME` which will close the connection when it's idle or not referred anymore.
However a different/shorter timeout (after connection is established) is useful to protect against any DDOS attempt trying to exhaust resources.

issue.title: base64: support encode/decode with URL and Filename Safe Alphabet
issue.body:
as title

[rfc4648 section-5, Base 64 Encoding with URL and Filename Safe Alphabet](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc4648#section-5)

comment.body:
I separate this feature into two commits. It contains two different solutions:
1.   the 1st commit only
    pj_base64_encode() is the standard encoder and pj_base64url_encode() is the urlsafe encoder.
    pj_base64_decode() can decode both standard and urlsafe string, no need to know the encoding type in advance.
2.  the 1st and 2nd together
    standard and  urlsafe use separate api pairs
   ( pj_base64_encode()/ pj_base64_decode()   and pj_base64url_encode()/ pj_base64url_decode()).
   They can't be mixed use, decoder must know the encoding type in advance.

We should decide which solution to use, if the 1st solution is adopted, i will delete the 2st commit.

issue.title: Use pjsip_cfg()-> endpt. disable_tcp_switch = 0 The port changes the hangup opportunity every 60s during the call. 477 Send failed (477/TM)
issue.body:
### Describe the bug

"I'm using PJSIP with a timer enabled, and I've set the timer's minimum value to 90 and maximum value to 120.  After the call is established, every 60 seconds, the port changes, and an UPDATE request is sent.  This leads to a situation where, after a long duration, the callee hangs up the call, but the caller can't disconnect.  From the SIP signaling, it seems that the port change is the cause, and I'm getting a '477 Send failed (477/TM)' error.  It appears that we're disconnecting from our end.  Is there a way to keep the connection alive or prevent the port from changing?  Note that I've used 'pjsip_cfg()->endpt. disable_tcp_switch = 0;'"

### Steps to reproduce

I set pjsua_acc_config cfg when I registered; cfg.reg_uri = Null calls are made directly
   cfg.use_timer = PJSUA_SIP_TIMER_ALWAYS;
   cfg.timer_setting.min_se = 90;
   cfg.timer_setting.sess_expires = 120;
pjsip_cfg()-> endpt. disable_tcp_switch = 0

2.13.1

issue.title: Unable to connect to PBX in Windows 11
Require SIPS on TLS calls is mandatory?
issue.body:
### Describe the bug

We set up the next settings:

- `secure_signaling=1` (TLS required, SIPS not),
- `rtp_secure_audio=2` (SRTP mandatory).

When we receive incoming INVITE on PJSIP which uses SIP+TLS, we get an error "SIPS required".
If we set `secure_signaling=0`, then there is no error. 

as per description: "1 - SRTP requires secure transport such as TLS", so in our opinion secure_signaling=1 should not require "SIPS".

Can you look into this?

### PJSIP version

2.13

comment.body:
Tried to reproduce using pjsua param `--use-srtp 2 --srtp-secure 1 --use-tls` and register to a SIP server via TLS so incoming call will arrive via TLS. A call with SRTP mandatory (e.g: using SDP media transport `RTP/SAVP`) can be accepted just fine.

Can you provide log file and/or reproducing steps using pjsua app?

issue.body:
For TCP there is a setting to close the incoming connection if there's no data received after a successful accept (`PJSIP_TCP_INITIAL_TIMEOUT`).

comment.body:
> > let me try to explain my point of view:
> > ```
> > 1. TLS entered handshake but there are no more data to perform the handshake -> timeout error
> > ```
> 
> So for TLS, the timer is started right after the TCP accept and before the TLS handshake, makes sense.
> 

There is already a handshake timer which handles this. The timeout setting is from `pj_ssl_sock_param::timeout`.
